DO  - 10.1016/j.ijleo.2022.169600
AB  - Quantum dot solar cell (QDSC) is a promising third-generation solar cell because of the theoretical prediction that its power conversion efficiency (PCE) can reach up to 66 % because of happening of a special phenomenon like multi-exciton generation (MEG). However, the PCE of QDSCs is very low in comparison to its theoretically predicted value. One of the reasons for low PCE could be the recombination of electron-hole pairs in the quasi-neutral region (QNR). To overcome the recombination losses and improve the efficiency of QDSC, the selection of an appropriate hole transport layer (HTL) and an electron transport layer (ETL) is essential. Cuprous oxide(Cu2O) is used as HTL, tetrabutylammonium iodide treated lead sulfide (PbS-TBAI) as an active layer, tungsten trioxide (WO3) as ETL and the PCE obtained is 15.51 %. Further, the energy band diagram (EBD), quantum efficiency (QE) curve and current-voltage (J-V) curve is obtained using the SCAPS-1D simulator. Further, we have optimized our device by varying thickness of PbS-TBAI, Cu2O and WO3, defect density at Cu2O/PbS-TBAI interface and PbS-TBAI/WO3 interface, doping density of Cu2O and WO3, electron affinity of Cu2O and WO3 and the PCE obtained after optimization is 23.05 %.
