AU  - Martin, Stolterfoht
TI  - Charge Generation and Transport Phenomena in Disordered Organic Semiconductors and Photovoltaic Diodes
LA  - eng
JF  - Queensland's Institutional Digital Repository (the University of Queensland)
PY  - 2016
PB  - The University of Queensland
DO  - 10.14264/uql.2016.676
AB  - Organic semiconductors are of great interest for a broad range of optoelectronic applicationsndue to their solution processability, chemical tunability and mechanical flexibility. In contrastnto traditional banded semiconductors, organic semiconductors are intrinsically disorderednsystems and exhibit therefore much lower charge carrier mobilities. They are also low dielectricnconstant systems n as such, their photo-excitations are excitonic at room temperature with thenelectron-hole pair remaining Coulombically-bound. Blending organic semiconductors withndiffering electron affinities, so-called electron acceptors and donors, creates molecularnheterojunctions which deliver the required driving force for exciton separation. These so-callednbulk heterojunctions (BHJs) are the dominant architecture for creating organic photovoltaicncells and photodetectors. However, not least because of an incomplete understanding of thenunderlying physical mechanism that control the conversion of photons to free charges, and thensubsequent extraction of these free charges to the electrodes, these organic optoelectronicnsystems still lag behind their inorganic counterparts.Motivated by these factors, the work described in this thesis advances the fundamentalnunderstanding of the loss mechanisms associated with charge photogeneration and chargentransport phenomena in BHJ organic solar cells and photodetectors, and presents newnexperimental methodologies to study these processes. The transport of photogenerated chargencarriers in the percolated donor: acceptor pathways towards the extracting electrodes has beennstudied in-depth via existing and newly developed transient photovoltage and steady-statencharacterization techniques. A simple but conclusive understanding has been developed whichnallows for minimization of the detrimental recombination of free charge carriers for givenndevice parameters such as film thickness, applied voltage and the mobility of the slower carrierntype (either electrons or holes). The modelsr predictions have been experimentally validated fornmany different (g 25) BHJ solar cell systems. Inspired by the need to selectively optimize thenprocesses which control the photocurrent output of the cell, such a charge photogeneration andnextraction, a technique to quantify and disentangle both efficiencies has been developed as annext step. Corroborated by transient absorption spectroscopy, the dynamics of the photocarrierngeneration process was examined. The results suggest that the so-called charge-transfer staten(CTS) separation limits the conversion of photons to free charges and the photocurrent outputnfrom short-circuit to the maximum power point, strongly depending on the slower carrier mobility. These findings were explained by the ability of the slower carriers to leave the donor:nacceptor interface via 1) a high enough mobility, 2) a sufficiently large domain size, and 3)nenough conduction pathways (entropy). This work also shows that the dynamics of chargenextraction and CTS dissociation are similar in the sense that both are critically controlled by thenslower carrier mobility. As such, the findings underline the importance of optimizing thenphotocarrier generation quantum yield via a high mobility of both charge carrier types, whichnsimultaneously maximizes the extraction yield as well. Lastly, the large benefit of redissociatingnCTS for all photovoltaic key parameters has been demonstrated for one of the mostnefficient organic solar cell systems to-date. Overall, the works presented in this thesis form ansimple but powerful model to explain the performance of organic solar cells and photodetectors,nand offer direct optimization guidelines through a more complete fundamental understandingnof charge generation and transport phenomena in these systems.n
