AU  - Parsai, E. Ishmael
AU  - Shvydka, Diana
TI  - Large Area Thin-Film CdTe as the Next-Generation X-Ray Detector for Medical Imaging Applications
LA  - eng
JF  - High-z Materials for X-ray Detection: Material Properties and Characterization Techniques
SP  - 23
EP  - 41
PY  - 2023
SN  - 3031209540, 3031209559, 9783031209543, 9783031209550
PB  - Springer International Publishing
DO  - 10.1007/978-3-031-20955-0_2
AB  - Cadmium telluride (CdTe) has been long recognized as a semiconductor material well suitable for high-energy (keV/MeV) X-ray detection in spectroscopic, imaging, and radiation dosimetry applications. Relative to the traditional silicon-based devices, CdTe offers superior (1) detection efficiency due to its high average atomic number and electron density, (2) charge collection owing to low effective ionization energy and high mobility-lifetime product, and (3) room temperature operation as the result of wide direct band gap, high lateral resistivity, and thus low leakage current. Remarkable radiation hardness is another crucial characteristic making CdTe devices especially attractive. Significant advancement in thin-film CdTe deposition techniques in recent years has made the material feasible for the low-cost large area fabrication commonly used in medical imaging. When compared to commercially available detection systems that use non-crystalline semiconductors, such as amorphous silicon or selenium, the high-Z CdTe-based devices are still preferable. In this chapter, we review our findings concerning use of CdTe for imaging applications in both diagnostic and therapeutic energy ranges. Monte Carlo radiation transport simulations were used for design and optimization of the direct detection type thin-film CdTe-based imagers. Systematic analysis of theoretically achievable performance based on intrinsic modulation transfer functions (MTF), noise power spectra (NPS), and detective quantum efficiencies (DQE) were computed for CdTe detectors of varying thickness, up to 1000 µm, under diagnostic and radiation therapy beam energies. Approaches to signal enhancement in a thin-film CdTe device based on addition of a front converter plate and utilization of electron backscattering are presented. The possibility of expanding a simple device design into a multilayer large area detector with immediate capabilities of high-energy photon imaging and spectroscopy, with subsequent extensions to Compton camera operations is explored. Finally, we present evaluation of thin-film CdTe radiation hardness under 6 MV photon source demonstrating no trend for material degradation under doses far exceeding typical radiation therapy detector lifetime dose. The study conducted on functional thin-film devices further supports utilization of CdTe for a next-generation high-energy photon detector.
ER  -

